      { type:'mc', q:"The Short-Run Aggregate Supply (SRAS) curve is upward sloping because:", options:["Firms face lower costs as prices rise","Higher prices make production more profitable, encouraging firms to produce more","Consumers demand more at higher prices","All factors of production are variable in the short run"], answer:1, explanation:"In the short run, some factor costs are fixed. When prices rise, firms' revenues increase but fixed costs don't, making production more profitable and incentivising increased output." },
      { type:'tf', q:"In the classical (long-run) model, the LRAS curve is vertical.", answer:true, explanation:"The LRAS is vertical at the economy's potential output (full employment level), reflecting the classical view that in the long run, all prices and wages are flexible and the economy returns to full employment." },
