      { type:'short', q:"Explain the difference between SRAS and LRAS.", answer:"SRAS (Short-Run Aggregate Supply) shows the relationship between the price level and output when at least one factor of production is fixed — it slopes upward. LRAS (Long-Run Aggregate Supply) represents the economy's potential output at full employment, where all factors are variable — it is vertical. SRAS shifts with changes in input costs; LRAS shifts with changes in productive capacity." },
